(31, 1, '2014-07-28 16:12:29', '2014-07-28 23:12:29', '<h3>Building the talent pool to protect the free and open web.</h3>\nMozilla Open Web Fellows work with some of the world’s <a title="Host Organizations" href="/host-organizations/">leading nonprofit organizations</a> to help ensure the public policy climate safeguards the Internet as a shared, global and public resource. During the 10-month paid fellowship, we will immerse the next generation of leaders in projects that address key needs with respect to digital freedom: better technical understanding among nonprofit organizations and policy makers of issues; a stronger affirmative agenda that creates better public awareness of internet policy issues; improved cross-sector coordination. Announcing the 2015 Mozilla Open Web Fellows Application -- We are looking for emerging leaders who have a passion for activism in Web issues, a track record of making and contributing to projects -- through technology, organizing, education, etc. -- and an interest in working with Mozilla and host nonprofit organizations on specific initiatives to advance and protect the open Web. Mozilla Open Web Fellows will:\n<ul>\n	<li><i class="fa fa-thumbs-up"></i>Contribute to existing and new projects that create a healthier, more trustworthy Web. This can be accomplished in multiple ways, including technology development, community organizing, education program development, and more.</li>\n	<li><i class="fa fa-comments"></i>Serve as technology advisors, mentors and ambassadors to the partner nonprofit organizations, helping to better inform the Web policy discussion.</li>\n	<li><i class="fa fa-users"></i>Work as a cohort, spending part time embedded within host organizations and part time in the Mozilla San Francisco office.</li>\n</ul>\n<a class="button" href="/application">Apply to be a Fellow</a>\n\nApplication deadline September 12\n<h4>We are thrilled to be partnering with the following Host Organizations</h4>\n<div class="org-grid">\n<a href="http://publicknowledge.org"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-150" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/Public-Knowledge.png" alt="Public-Knowledge" width="250" height="39" /></a> <a href="http://amnesty.org"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-121" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/amnesty.jpg" alt="amnesty" width="250" height="106" /></a> <a href="http://freepress.net"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-123" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/freepress.jpg" alt="freepress" width="250" height="109" /></a>\n<a href="http://oti.newamerica.net"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-124" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/oti.jpg" alt="oti" width="250" height="75" /></a> <a href="https://www.aclu.org/"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-125" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/acluf.jpg" alt="acluf" width="250" height="94" /></a>\n\n\n<small>Photo: Elvert Barnes via Flickr</small>', 'Open Web Fellows', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '6-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-07-28 16:12:29', '2014-07-28 23:12:29', '', 6, 'http://localhost/mozilla/2014/07/07/6-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(32, 1, '2014-07-07 17:47:41', '2014-07-08 00:47:41', '<h3>Open Web Fellows -- Building the talent pool to protect the free and open web.</h3>\r\nMozilla Open Web Fellows work with some of the world’s leading nonprofit organizations to help ensure the public policy climate safeguards the Internet as a shared, global and public resource.\r\n\r\nDuring the 10-month paid fellowship, we will immerse the next generation of leaders in projects that address key needs with respect to digital freedom: better technical understanding among nonprofit organizations and policy makers of issues; a stronger affirmative agenda that creates better public awareness of internet policy issues; improved cross-sector coordination.\r\n\r\nAnnouncing the 2015 Mozilla Open Web Fellows Application -- We are looking for emerging leaders who have a passion for activism in Web issues, a track record of making and contributing to projects -- through technology, organizing, education, etc. -- and an interest in working with Mozilla and host nonprofit organizations on specific initiatives to advance and protect the open Web. Mozilla Open Web Fellows will:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Contribute to existing and new projects that create a healthier, more trustworthy Web. This can be accomplished in multiple ways, including technology development, community organizing, education program development, and more.</li>\r\n	<li>Serve as technology advisors, mentors and ambassadors to the partner nonprofit organizations, helping to better inform the Web policy discussion.</li>\r\n	<li>Work as a cohort, spending part time embedded within host organizations and part time in the Mozilla San Francisco office.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMeet our Host Nonprofits: We are excited to announce the nonprofit organizations that will serve as hosts for the 2015 Fellows', 'Open Web Fellows', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '6-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-07 17:47:41', '2014-07-08 00:47:41', '', 6, 'http://localhost/mozilla/2014/07/07/6-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(33, 1, '2014-07-08 10:07:21', '2014-07-08 17:07:21', '<h3>Open Web Fellows -- Building the talent pool to protect the free and open web.</h3>\r\nMozilla Open Web Fellows work with some of the world’s leading nonprofit organizations to help ensure the public policy climate safeguards the Internet as a shared, global and public resource. During the 10-month paid fellowship, we will immerse the next generation of leaders in projects that address key needs with respect to digital freedom: better technical understanding among nonprofit organizations and policy makers of issues; a stronger affirmative agenda that creates better public awareness of internet policy issues; improved cross-sector coordination. Announcing the 2015 Mozilla Open Web Fellows Application -- We are looking for emerging leaders who have a passion for activism in Web issues, a track record of making and contributing to projects -- through technology, organizing, education, etc. -- and an interest in working with Mozilla and host nonprofit organizations on specific initiatives to advance and protect the open Web. Mozilla Open Web Fellows will:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Contribute to existing and new projects that create a healthier, more trustworthy Web. This can be accomplished in multiple ways, including technology development, community organizing, education program development, and more.</li>\r\n	<li>Serve as technology advisors, mentors and ambassadors to the partner nonprofit organizations, helping to better inform the Web policy discussion.</li>\r\n	<li>Work as a cohort, spending part time embedded within host organizations and part time in the Mozilla San Francisco office.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMeet our Host Nonprofits. [ link to policy contributors page? ]', 'Open Web Fellows', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '6-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-08 10:07:21', '2014-07-08 17:07:21', '', 6, 'http://localhost/mozilla/2014/07/08/6-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
