o office.\r\nIn 2015, the Fellows will be based with:\r\nINSERT ORGS\r\n\r\nWe make every attempt to match skills of Fellows with needs of partner organizations when matching Fellow to organization.\r\n\r\nWhat are you looking for with the example projects on the application?\r\nWe want to see three projects that you are proud of. Tell us why you’re excited about the project, and if you made the project has part of a team, describe the contribution that you made. The examples you include are not shared beyond the small pool of application reviewers.\r\n\r\nWhat if my example projects don’t include open source or technology contributions?\r\nThat’s ok. We understand that a lot of people have done work that is not open source and that a lot of policy and advocacy work is not technology specific. You will be building in the open and contributing back to open source projects as a Fellow, but it is not a requirement to have done this before applying.\r\n\r\nWhat is the timeline after the Fellowship deadline closes?\r\nThe Fellowship application opened on {INSERT DATE} and closes September 12, 2014. After September 12, all applications will be reviewed by a small reviewing panel. By early October, a final batch of 20-30 semifinalists will be selected and interviews conducted. Finalists will be notified by mid October and a public announcement of our 2015 fellows will be made at the Mozilla Festival in London October 24, 2014.\r\n\r\nWhat kind of competition are you expecting with the Fellowship?\r\nThis is the first year of the Open Web Fellows search process, so it’s difficult to gauge the level of competition. For comparison, the Mozilla-Knight OpenNews Fellowship program receives hundreds of qualified applications for a limited amount of Fellowship openings.\r\nIn terms of the applicant pool, we are committed to matching the skills of the Fellow to the needs of the news organization. It’s a very individualized matching process.\r\n\r\nHow does the application review and matching process work?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Applications are submitted through a Google form [ link ] and are visible at the time they are submitted, but formal review does not begin until after the application deadline closes on September 12.</li>\r\n	<li>Mozilla''s policy and advocacy staff review all of the applications and cull the batch to a manageable number for the partner organizations to review.</li>\r\n	<li>The partners review this shorter list and submit a list of the five people they are most interested in learning more about.</li>\r\n	<li>These semifinalists are contacted for interviews. Applicants who are not moving forward in the selection process are notified.</li>\r\n	<li>Mozilla’s policy and advocacy team conduct short, standardized interviews with the semifinalists, asking a few questions that are about vision and skills/practical considerations.</li>\r\n	<li>The notes from these interviews are submitted back to the partner organizations for review, and the partners are able to pick their top three finalists from the entire pool of semifinalists, not just the five they initially submitted.</li>\r\n	<li>The semifinalists that are not moving forward are notified of their application status.</li>\r\n	<li>The partner organization and Mozilla’s policy and advocacy team has a much longer interview with each of the partner organization’s top three candidates. This interview is a chance for the partner organization and the finalist to learn more about each other and what to expect from a Fellowship at that host organization.</li>\r\n	<li>In consultation with Mozilla’s policy and advocacy team and the partner organizations, the final Fellow selection is made for each organization.</li>\r\n	<li>The selected Fellows are notified and given an opportunity to ask additional questions of the partner organization and Mozilla.</li>\r\n	<li>The finalists that were not selected as Fellows are notified of their application status.</li>\r\n	<li>A public announcement of the Fellows is made at the Mozilla Festival.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWhat is the timeline for the Fellowship?\r\n2015 Fellowships begin in January 2015 and last for 10 months. Each Fellows'' start date will be individualized for the needs of that Fellow and the partner organization.\r\n\r\nWhat type of projects do the fellows work on?\r\nThat is dictated by the partner organization and the Fellow. We expect that these projects will reflect a range of policy and advocacy activities, including program/campaign development, technology issue analysis, data crunching, etc. We’re looking for talented people who want to collaborate with partner organizations to advance existing projects and to create new ones. In collaboration with Mozilla, the other Fellows, and the partner organizations, Fellows get a lot of room to figure out what the projects will be.\r\n\r\nAre you still accepting applications for host organizations?\r\nNo, we are not accepting host newsroom applications at this time.\r\n\r\nWhy is Mozilla interested in policy and advocacy?\r\n\r\nWho is sponsoring the Open Web Fellows Program?\r\nFord, Google, etc.\r\n\r\nHow do I contact you?\r\nWe’re very reachable. You can e-mail us, find us on Twitter or Facebook, reach us at our monthly community calls, and even catch us on IRC via the #openweb channel on irc.mozilla.org. We’d love to hear from you and are happy to answer any questions you may have.', 'FAQ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '10-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-08 10:22:23', '2014-07-08 17:22:23', '', 10, 'http://localhost/mozilla/2014/07/08/10-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
