(204, 1, '2014-07-29 11:32:37', '2014-07-29 18:32:37', '<h3>Building the talent pool to protect the free and open web.</h3>\r\nMozilla Open Web Fellows work with some of the world’s <a title="Host Organizations" href="/host-organizations/">leading nonprofit organizations</a> to help ensure the public policy climate safeguards the Internet as a shared, global and public resource. During the 10-month paid fellowship, we will immerse the next generation of leaders in projects that address key needs with respect to digital freedom: better technical understanding among nonprofit organizations and policy makers of issues; a stronger affirmative agenda that creates better public awareness of internet policy issues; improved cross-sector coordination. Announcing the 2015 Mozilla Open Web Fellows Application -- We are looking for emerging leaders who have a passion for activism in Web issues, a track record of making and contributing to projects -- through technology, organizing, education, etc. -- and an interest in working with Mozilla and host nonprofit organizations on specific initiatives to advance and protect the open Web. Mozilla Open Web Fellows will:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><i class="fa fa-thumbs-up"></i>Contribute to existing and new projects that create a healthier, more trustworthy Web. This can be accomplished in multiple ways, including technology development, community organizing, education program development, and more.</li>\r\n	<li><i class="fa fa-comments"></i>Serve as technology advisors, mentors and ambassadors to the partner nonprofit organizations, helping to better inform the Web policy discussion.</li>\r\n	<li><i class="fa fa-users"></i>Work as a cohort, spending part time embedded within host organizations and part time in the Mozilla San Francisco office.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a class="button" href="/application">Apply to be a Fellow</a>\r\n\r\nApplication deadline September 12\r\n<h4>We are thrilled to be partnering with the following Host Organizations</h4>\r\n<div id="org-grid">\r\n<a href="http://publicknowledge.org"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-150" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/Public-Knowledge.png" alt="Public-Knowledge" width="250" height="39" /></a> <a href="http://amnesty.org"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-121" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/amnesty.jpg" alt="amnesty" width="250" height="106" /></a> <a href="http://freepress.net"><img src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/freepress.png" alt="freepress" width="250" height="109" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-200" /></a>\r\n<a href="http://oti.newamerica.net"><img class="alignleft size-full" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/oti.png" alt="oti" width="250" height="75" /></a> <a href="https://www.aclu.org/"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-125" src="http://localhost/mozilla/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/07/acluf.jpg" alt="acluf" width="250" height="94" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<small>Photo: Elvert Barnes via Flickr</small>', 'Open Web Fellows', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '6-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-29 11:32:37', '2014-07-29 18:32:37', '', 6, 'http://localhost/mozilla/2014/07/29/6-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
